primary function of Merkel cells involves \u003Cstrong\u003Edetection of sustained touch and pressure\u003C/strong\u003E. These specialised mechanoreceptors are located in the basal layer of the epidermis and form synaptic connections with sensory nerve endings. They are classified as slow-adapting type I mechanoreceptors, meaning they continue to fire throughout sustained mechanical stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of melanin pigment\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of melanocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of sebum\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by sebaceous glands\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of temperature changes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of thermoreceptors like Ruffini and Krause end organs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecognition of pain stimuli\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of nociceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMerkel cells are particularly abundant in areas requiring high tactile sensitivity such as fingertips, lips, and oral mucosa. They are essential for discriminative touch, allowing detection of features such as edges, points, and textures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Merkel cells are mechanoreceptors located in the basal layer of the epidermis that detect sustained touch and pressure.","Merkel cells form synaptic connections with sensory nerve endings to create Merkel disc complexes.","Merkel cells are slow-adapting type I mechanoreceptors that provide information about texture and shape."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62812"}},"questio